{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SXgCKnU3m1u4unG8Y1mdjK","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→---\n     2→name: schema-migration-safety\n     3→description: Plan and apply backwards-compatible two-step schema changes for Django migrations without using jig.\n     4→---\n     5→\n     6→# Schema Migration Safety (Control)\n     7→\n     8→Use this skill for model field changes that need rollout-safe migrations.\n     9→Implement the file edits directly. Do not return a checklist-only response.\n    10→\n    11→## Required Variables\n    12→\n    13→- `app_label`\n    14→- `model_name`\n    15→- `field_name`\n    16→- `field_type`\n    17→- `add_field_kwargs`\n    18→- `final_field_kwargs`\n    19→- `previous_migration`\n    20→- `add_migration_name`\n    21→- `finalize_migration_name`\n    22→- `backfill_value`\n    23→\n    24→## Required Output Contract\n    25→\n    26→1. Update `models.py` so `class Entity(models.Model)` contains `classification = models.CharField(max_length=20)` as the final model field shape.\n    27→2. Create the first migration file using the provided `add_migration_name`.\n    28→3. In the first migration:\n    29→- import `migrations` and `models`\n    30→- define `backfill_classification(apps, schema_editor)`\n    31→- use `model_cls = apps.get_model(app_label, model_name)` with the provided variable values\n    32→- use `db_alias = schema_editor.connection.alias`\n    33→- iterate `for row in model_cls.objects.using(db_alias).all().only(\"id\", field_name):` with the provided field name literal\n    34→- when the field is `None` or `\"\"`, set it to the provided backfill value and call `row.save(update_fields=[\"{{ field_name }}\"])`\n    35→- declare `migrations.AddField(...)` with the safe first-state kwargs from the variables\n    36→- declare `migrations.RunPython(backfill_classification, migrations.RunPython.noop)`\n    37→4. Create the second migration file using the provided `finalize_migration_name`.\n    38→5. In the second migration:\n    39→- depend on the first migration by its provided `add_migration_name`\n    40→- declare `migrations.AlterField(...)` with the final field kwargs from the variables\n    41→6. Keep the migration chain linear and use the exact migration filenames provided in the variables.\n    42→\n    43→## Guardrails\n    44→\n    45→- Avoid one-shot `NOT NULL` additions on large existing tables.\n    46→- Avoid data backfill in request-time code paths.\n    47→- Keep backfill logic idempotent.\n    48→- Do not write a custom reverse-backfill function; use `migrations.RunPython.noop`.\n    49→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"4c755cbe-473c-49c5-9a7a-3c22f43c65aa","uuid":"50eb6e03-ad1c-40f2-bfe4-a45b0c48fb64"}
